***************************************************************************
                          Bracketing and Indentation
***************************************************************************

The sole purpose of good indentation is to make code readable. Poor
indentation makes it difficult to find bugs in code, and is otherwise
annoying to other people who have to read your code.

Bracketing of code happens when braces (i.e. { } ) are used to specify
one or more lines of code as being part of a particular execution path.
During execution, the execution path may or may not enter the section
between the braces. If it does enter, then the code is executed normally.
If not, NONE of that code is executed. Sometimes (e.g. in a for loop),
after executing the code between braces, the program will return to the
start of the braced section.

Indentation should always be consistent in your code. Common sizes of
indentation are 2, 4 or 8 characters per indentation level (I personally
recommend 4.) This means that the first "level" of code is at 0 spaces
in, the second is 4 spaces in, the third is 8 spaces in etc. for a 4
space indentation scheme.


When do you indent?
-------------------
- All code inside a function should be indented one level.
- All code inside braces should be indented one level more than the
  level the braces themselves are at.
- Long lines of code that are broken up into multiple lines should
  have the second and subsequent lines indented one level more than
  the first line.
- Literal text broken into multiple lines (with \) should NOT be
  indented.


